# Introduction

Let $$\label{eq:BVsys}
   (H_\theta \Phi)_n   = B_{n+1}(\theta)\Phi_{n+1}+ B_n^{(*)}(\theta) \Phi_{n-1}+ V_n (\theta)\Phi_n$$ where $F_n(\theta):=F(\theta+n\omega)$ for any $d\times d$-matrix valued function. We set $B^{(*)}(\theta)=(B(\theta))^*$ for $\theta\in \mathbb T$, and require it to be the analytic extension of $(B(\theta))^*$ off of the real torus. Here $\theta,\omega\in\mathbb{T}^b$ and we assume that $\omega$ is Diophantine, i.e., $$\begin{aligned}
    \omega\in \mathrm{DC}:=&\bigcup_{a>0, A>b} \mathrm{DC}_{a,A}, \text{ where}\\
    \mathrm{DC}_{a,A}=&\left\{\omega\in \mathbb T^b:\, \|k\cdot \omega\|_{\mathbb T^b}\geq \frac{a}{|k|^A}\, \text{ for all } k\in \mathbb Z^d\setminus \{0\}\right\}.
\end{aligned}$$ We further assume that $B,V\in C^{\omega}(\mathbb{T}^b_{\eta}, \mathrm{Mat}(d,\mathbb C))$ are analytic, where $$\mathbb T^b_{\eta}:=\{\theta+i\varepsilon:\, \theta\in \mathbb T^b,\, \varepsilon\in \mathbb R^d,  \text{ and } |\varepsilon|\leq \eta\}$$with some positive $\eta>0$. We assume throughout the paper that $V$ is Hermitian, and that $B$ is invertible ($\det B(\theta)\neq 0$ for any $\theta\in \mathbb T^b_{\eta}$). The difference equation $H_{\theta} \Phi=E\Phi$ is equivalent to the cocycle $$\begin{aligned}
\label{def:M_E}
  \mathcal{C}&\::  (\theta,\Psi)\in \mathbb{T}^b\times \mathbb C^{2d}\mapsto (\theta+\omega, M_E(\theta)\Psi), \notag  \\
  \quad M_{E}(\theta) &= \left [ \begin{matrix}
   ( E-V(\theta))B(\theta)^{-1}  & -B^{(*)}(\theta) \\
  B(\theta)^{-1} & 0 
\end{matrix}\right]  
\end{aligned}$$ in the sense that for $n\ge1$, $$\mathcal{C}^n (\theta,\Psi)=(\theta+n\omega, M_{n,E}(\theta)\Psi), \quad M_{n,E}(\theta)=\prod_{j=n-1}^0 M_E(\theta+j\omega), \quad 
\Psi_n:=\binom{B_{n}\Phi_n}{\Phi_{n-1}}$$ satisfies $\Psi_n = M_{n,E} (\theta) \Psi_0$. Since $M_E(\theta)$ is (complex) symplectic, see <a href="#def:symp" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="def:symp">[def:symp]</a>, for $\theta\in \mathbb T^b$, the Lyapunov exponents $\{L_j(\omega,M_E)\}_{j=1}^{2d}$, see definition in <a href="#def:LE" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="def:LE">[def:LE]</a>, satisfy $L_{2d-j}=-L_j$ for $1\le j\le d$. In analogy with we establish localization for $H_0$ under a nonvanishing condition on the Lyapunov exponents.

Our next theorem, which can be seen as a generalization of \*Theorem 1.6, concerns arithmetic Anderson localization for long-range scalar-valued Jacobi matrices with potential defined on the one-dimensional torus $\mathbb T$. For the one-dimensional torus, there is another quantity, Avila’s quantized acceleration of the cocycle, which we denote by $\kappa^d(\omega,M_E)$, that plays a crucial role in determining the spectral behavior of the corresponding operator. The acceleration was first introduced by Avila in his global theory paper for $\mathrm{SL}(2,\mathbb R)$ cocycles, and extended to higher dimensional cocycles in . A characterization of the acceleration, for scalar valued Schrödinger operator $d=1$ and for Diophantine $\omega$, through the zeros of Dirichlet determinants was proved in .

In this paper, we give a characterization of the acceleration $\kappa^d(\omega,M_E)$ associated to Jacobi block matrices with $d\geq 2$ in terms of the zero count of the finite volume determinants with periodic boundary condition. See Theorem <a href="#thm:Riesz_un" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:Riesz_un">35</a>. We also give applications of such characterization in arithmetic Anderson localization for various models. All of our arithmetic Anderson localization results concern the one-dimensional torus $\mathbb T$. For $\theta,\omega\in \mathbb T$, let $$\begin{aligned}
\label{def:tH}
    (\tilde{H}_{\theta}\phi)_n=\sum_{1\leq |k|\leq d} v_k\phi_{n-k}+g(\theta+nd^{-1}\omega) \phi_n,
\end{aligned}$$ where throughout the paper we assume that $g\in C_{\eta}^{\omega}(\mathbb T,\mathbb R)$ is real-valued and non-constant and $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:basic_assume_v}
\overline{v_k}=v_{-k} \text{ for any } 1\leq k\leq d, \text{ and }
v_d\neq 0.
\end{aligned}$$ Note that we use $d^{-1}\omega$ as the frequency in $\tilde{H}_{\theta}$ to better fit into the framework of <a href="#eq:BVsys" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:BVsys">[eq:BVsys]</a>. Let $A_E$ be the corresponding $1$-step transfer matrix (see <a href="#def:A_E" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="def:A_E">[def:A_E]</a>) and $\kappa^d(d^{-1}\omega,A_E)$ be its acceleration, which is an integer as long as $L_d(d^{-1}\omega,A_E)>0$ (see \*Lemma 6.4).

<div id="thm:acceleration=1" class="theorem">

The proof of Theorem <a href="#thm:skew_shift" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:skew_shift">7</a> is built on establishing Anderson localization for the dual model, obtained as a corollary of Theorem <a href="#thm:acceleration=d_2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:acceleration=d_2">4</a>. We actually prove a stronger almost localization result, see Theorem <a href="#thm:sk_dual_almost_AL" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:sk_dual_almost_AL">53</a>. Combining almost localization with the quantitative duality techniques from , one should be able to prove quantitative almost reducibility of $H^{sk}_{\lambda,x,y,p/q}$ and conclude purely absolutely continuous spectrum for this operator through the perturbative theory of Eliasson . We leave this and other applications of quantitative almost reducibility of this operator for future work.

In Section <a href="#sec:coupledHarper" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:coupledHarper">8</a>, we establish some properties of the coupled Harper operators ($\omega$ Diophantine) $$\label{eq:Harpx2}
     \begin{split}
          \phi_{n+1}+\phi_{n-1}+\epsilon\psi_n + 2\lambda_1 \cos(2\pi(x+n\omega)) \phi_n &= E\phi_n \\
     \psi_{n+1}+\psi_{n-1}+\epsilon\phi_n + 2\lambda_2 \cos(2\pi(x+n\omega)) \psi_n &= E\psi_n
     \end{split}$$ where $\epsilon\in\mathbb R$ is small, and $\lambda_2\ge \lambda_1>0$. This falls under the scope of <a href="#eq:BVsys" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:BVsys">[eq:BVsys]</a>. Amongst other results, we show that for $\lambda_2\gg 1$ and $0<\epsilon,\lambda_1\ll 1$, both Anderson localization and a.c. states occur on sets of positive measure of energies $E$ in the spectrum of this system. Moreover, it follows from the two-sided Oseledets theorem, see \*Theorem 4.2, that the states associated with the a.c. spectrum are not of hybrid type. I.e., they are truly extended states and cannot exhibit exponential decay to one side.

In Section <a href="#sec:coupledHarper" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:coupledHarper">8</a>, we establish some properties of the coupled Harper operators ($\omega$ Diophantine) $$\label{eq:Harpx2}
     \begin{split}
          \phi_{n+1}+\phi_{n-1}+\epsilon\psi_n + 2\lambda_1 \cos(2\pi(x+n\omega)) \phi_n &= E\phi_n \\
     \psi_{n+1}+\psi_{n-1}+\epsilon\phi_n + 2\lambda_2 \cos(2\pi(x+n\omega)) \psi_n &= E\psi_n
     \end{split}$$ where $\epsilon\in\mathbb R$ is small, and $\lambda_2\ge \lambda_1>0$. This falls under the scope of <a href="#eq:BVsys" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:BVsys">[eq:BVsys]</a>. Amongst other results, we show that for $\lambda_2\gg 1$ and $0<\epsilon,\lambda_1\ll 1$, both Anderson localization and a.c. states occur on sets of positive measure of energies $E$ in the spectrum of this system. Moreover, it follows from the two-sided Oseledets theorem, see \*Theorem 4.2, that the states associated with the a.c. spectrum are not of hybrid type. I.e., they are truly extended states and cannot exhibit exponential decay to one side.

The rest of the paper is organized as follows: some preliminaries are presented in Section <a href="#sec:Pre" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:Pre">2</a>, and some technical lemmas are in Section <a href="#sec:lemma" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:lemma">2.6</a>. The proofs of these lemmas are in Section <a href="#sec:Zaehler" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:Zaehler">3</a> for the numerator of the Green’s function, and Section <a href="#sec:nenner" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:nenner">4</a> for the lower bound of the denominator, respectively. The main theorems are proved in Sections <a href="#sec:main" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:main">5.1</a> (Theorem <a href="#thm:main" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:main">1</a>) and Section <a href="#sec:AL_arithmetic" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:AL_arithmetic">5.2</a> (Theorems <a href="#thm:acceleration=1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:acceleration=1">2</a>, <a href="#thm:acceleration=d_2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:acceleration=d_2">4</a>). The applications are discussed in Section <a href="#sec:XY_sk" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:XY_sk">6</a> (XY-spin chain and skew-shift), Section <a href="#sec:application" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:application">7</a> (stacked graphene models), and Section <a href="#sec:coupledHarper" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="sec:coupledHarper">8</a> (coupled Harper’s model).

\end{aligned}$$

On the other hand, as a scalar-valued operator, the eigenvalue equation $\tilde{H}_{\theta}\phi=E\phi$ can also be rewritten as: $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:tranfer_hH_varepsilon_1step}
\left(\begin{matrix}
\phi_{n+d}\\
\vdots\\
\phi_{n+1}\\
\phi_n\\
\vdots\\
\phi_{n-d+1}
\end{matrix}\right)
=A_{E}(\theta+nd^{-1}\omega)
\left(\begin{matrix}
\phi_{n+d-1}\\
\vdots\\
\phi_{n}\\
\phi_{n-1}\\
\vdots\\
\phi_{n-d}\end{matrix}\right),
\end{aligned}$$ where $$\label{def:A_E}
A_{E}(\theta):=
\frac{1}{v_{-d}}
\left(\begin{matrix}
-v_{1-d} &\cdots &-v_{-1} &E-g(\theta) &| &-v_1 &\cdots &-v_{d-1} &-v_d\\
v_{-d} & & & &|\\
&\ddots & & &| & \\
& &v_{-d}  & &| &\\
\hline
& & &v_{-d} &| &\\
& & & &| &v_{-d} \\
& & & &| & &\ddots\\
& & & &| & & &v_{-d}
\end{matrix}\right).$$ It is easy to verify that for any $\theta\in \mathbb T^b_{\eta}$, $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:matrix_M=A}
    M_E(\theta)=\mathrm{diag}(B,I_d)\cdot \prod_{j=d-1}^0 A_E(\theta+jd^{-1}\omega)\cdot \mathrm{diag}(B^{-1},I_d),
\end{aligned}$$

A complex matrix $M\in \mathrm{Mat}(2d,\mathbb C)$ is symplectic if $$\begin{aligned}
\label{def:symp}
    M^*\Omega M=\Omega,
\end{aligned}$$ where $$\begin{aligned}
    \Omega=\left(\begin{matrix} 0 & I_d\\ -I_d &0\end{matrix}\right).
\end{aligned}$$ One can easily verify that for $M_E$ as in <a href="#def:M_E" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="def:M_E">[def:M_E]</a>, and $E\in \mathbb R$, $\theta\in \mathbb T^b$, $$\begin{aligned}
    (M_E(\theta))^* \Omega M_E(\theta)=\Omega.
\end{aligned}$$ However for $\theta\in \mathbb T^b\setminus \mathbb T$, $M_E(\theta)$ is in general not symplectic.

## Lyapunov exponents

Let $(\omega, A)\in (\mathbb T^b, C^{\omega}(\mathbb T, \mathrm{Mat}(k,\mathbb C)))$. Let $$\begin{aligned}
A_n(\omega,\theta)=A(\theta+(n-1)\omega)\cdots A(\theta).
\end{aligned}$$ Let the finite-scale and infinite-scale Lyapunov exponents be defined as $$\begin{aligned}
\label{def:LE}
L_{j,(n)}(\omega, A):=\frac{1}{n}\int_{\mathbb T^b} \log \sigma_j(A_n(\omega,\theta))\, \mathrm{d}\theta, \text{ for } 1\leq j\leq k,
\end{aligned}$$ where $\sigma_j(A)$ is the $j$-th singular value of $A$, and the $j$-th Lyapunov exponent $$\begin{aligned}
L_j(\omega, A)=\lim_{n\to\infty}L_{j,(n)}(\omega, A).
\end{aligned}$$ It is easy to see that for $1\leq j\leq k$, $$\begin{aligned}
L^j_{(n)}(\omega, A):=\sum_{\ell=1}^j L_{\ell,(n)}(\omega, A)=\frac{1}{n}\int_{\mathbb T}\log \|\textstyle{\bigwedge^j} A_n(\omega,\theta)\|\, \mathrm{d}\theta,
\end{aligned}$$ where $\textstyle{\bigwedge^j} A$ is the $j$-th exterior power of $A$. Similarly $L^j(\omega,A)=\sum_{\ell=1}^j L_{\ell}(\omega, A)$.

We also denote the phase complexified Lyapunov exponents $L_{j,(n)}(\omega,A(\cdot+i\varepsilon))=:L_{j,(n),\varepsilon}(\omega,A)$, $L_j(\omega,A(\cdot+i\varepsilon))=:L_{j,\varepsilon}(\omega,A)$, $L^j_{(n)}(\omega,A_E(\cdot+i\varepsilon))=:L^j_{(n),\varepsilon}(\omega,A_E)$, and $L^j(\omega,A_E(\cdot+i\varepsilon))=:L^j_{\varepsilon}(\omega,A_E)$, respectively. Here $\varepsilon\in \mathbb R^b$. Since $M_E(\theta)$ is symplectic for $\theta\in \mathbb T^b$, for each $1\leq j\leq d$ $$\begin{aligned}
    L_{j,\varepsilon=0}(\omega,M_E)=-L_{2d+1-j,\varepsilon=0}(\omega,M_E).
\end{aligned}$$ However the above is in general not true if $\varepsilon\neq 0$.

## Avila’s acceleration

Within this subsection, we restrict to the 1-d torus $\mathbb T$. Let $(\omega, A)\in (\mathbb T, C^{\omega}(\mathbb T, \mathrm{SL}(2, \mathbb R)))$. The (top) Lyapunov exponent $L^1_{\varepsilon}(\omega,A)=L_{1,\varepsilon}(\omega, A)$ is a convex and even function in $\varepsilon$. Avila defined the acceleration to be the right-derivative as follows: $$\begin{aligned}
\kappa^1_{\varepsilon}(\omega, A):=\lim_{\varepsilon'\to 0^+} \frac{L^1_{\varepsilon+\varepsilon'}(\omega, A)-L^1_{\varepsilon}(\omega, A)}{2\pi \varepsilon'}.
\end{aligned}$$ As a cornerstone of his global theory , he showed that for $A\in \mathrm{SL}(2,\mathbb R)$ and irrational $\alpha$, $\kappa_{\varepsilon}^1(\omega, A)\in \mathbb Z$ is always quantized.

The concept of acceleration was further extended to $(\omega,A)\in (\mathbb T,C^{\omega}(\mathbb T, \mathrm{Mat}(k,\mathbb C)))$ in , where for $1\leq j\leq k$, $$\begin{aligned}
    \kappa^j_{\varepsilon}(\omega,A):=\lim_{\varepsilon'\to 0^+} \frac{L^j_{\varepsilon+\varepsilon'}(\omega, A)-L^j_{\varepsilon}(\omega, A)}{2\pi \varepsilon'}.
\end{aligned}$$

By <a href="#eq:matrix_M=A" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:matrix_M=A">[eq:matrix_M=A]</a>, for $|\varepsilon|\leq \eta$ and each $1\leq j\leq 2d$, $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:M=A}
    L_{j,\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)=d\cdot L_{j,\varepsilon}(d^{-1}\omega,A_E),
\end{aligned}$$ and $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:kappa_M=dA}
\kappa^j_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)=d\cdot \kappa^j_{\varepsilon}(d^{-1}\omega,A_E).
\end{aligned}$$

By <a href="#eq:matrix_M=A" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:matrix_M=A">[eq:matrix_M=A]</a>, for $|\varepsilon|\leq \eta$ and each $1\leq j\leq 2d$, $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:M=A}
    L_{j,\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)=d\cdot L_{j,\varepsilon}(d^{-1}\omega,A_E),
\end{aligned}$$ and $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:kappa_M=dA}
\kappa^j_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)=d\cdot \kappa^j_{\varepsilon}(d^{-1}\omega,A_E).
\end{aligned}$$

Recall that $B,V$ are analytic functions on $\mathbb T_{\eta}$ for some $\eta>0$. We may shrink $\eta$ when necessary such that $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:L_linear}
L^d_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)=L^d_{\varepsilon=0}(\omega,M_E)+2\pi \kappa^d_{\varepsilon=0}(\omega,M_E)|\varepsilon|
\end{aligned}$$ holds for any $|\varepsilon|\leq \eta$. For the rest of the paper, when $\varepsilon=0$, we shall omit $\varepsilon$ from various notations of Lyapunov exponents and accelerations. On some occasions, we shall also omit $\omega$ and $M_E$ in $L^j(\omega,M_E)$, $L_j(\omega,M_E)$ and $\kappa^d(\omega,M_E)$.

## Green’s function and Poisson formula

As in we work with finite volume Hamiltonians under periodic boundary conditions. Thus, we define the $nd\times nd$ matrices $$\begin{aligned}
\label{def:Pn}
P_{n}(\theta)=
\left(\begin{matrix}
V(\theta+(n-1)\omega) & B^{(*)}(\theta+(n-1)\omega) & &  &B(\theta)\\
B(\theta+(n-1)\omega) &V(\theta+(n-2)\omega) &\ddots \\
& \ddots &\ddots &\ddots \\
& &\ddots &\ddots &B^{(*)}(\theta+\omega)\\
B^{(*)}(\theta) & & &B(\theta+\omega) &V(\theta)
\end{matrix}\right),
\end{aligned}$$ Let $$\begin{aligned}
\label{def:fn}
f_{E,n}(\theta):=\det(P_{n}(\theta)-E)
\end{aligned}$$ and $$\begin{aligned}
\label{def:Green}
G_{E,n}(\theta):=(P_{n}(\theta)-E)^{-1}
\end{aligned}$$ be the finite volume Green’s function with the periodic boundary conditions. By Cramer’s rule $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:mufn}
G_{E,n}(\theta;x,y)=\frac{\mu_{n,x,y}(\theta)}{f_{E,n}(\theta)},
\end{aligned}$$ where $\mu_{n,x,y}(\theta)$ is the determinant of the submatrix of $(P_{n}(\theta)-E)$ defined by deleting the $x$-th row and $y$-th column. Let $u$ be a solution to the eigenvalue equation ${H}_{\theta}u=Eu$. For any $k\in \mathbb Z$ the following Poisson formula holds for all $k\leq m\leq k+nd-1$: $$\begin{aligned}
{u}_m=&\sum_{y_1=0}^{d-1} G_{E,n}(\theta+k\omega; m-k, y_1) \left(B^{(*)}(\theta)\cdot \left(\begin{matrix}{u}_{k+nd-1}-{u}_{k-1}\\ \vdots\\ {u}_{k+(n-1)d}-{u}_{k-d}\end{matrix}\right)\right)_{y_1}\\
&\qquad+\sum_{y_2=(n-1)d}^{nd-1}G_{E,n}(\theta+k\omega;m-k,y_2)\left(B(\theta) \left(\begin{matrix}u_{k+d-1}\\ \vdots\\ u_k\end{matrix}\right)-B(\theta+n\omega)\left(\begin{matrix}{u}_{k+(n+1)d-1}\\ \vdots \\ {u}_{k+nd}\end{matrix}\right)\right)_{y_2-(n-1)d},
\end{aligned}$$ in which $(M)_y$ refers to the element of vector $M$ in row $y$. This implies $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:Poisson_exp}
|{u}_m|\leq &C_d \|B\|_{\mathbb T^b, \infty}\cdot \max_{y\in \{0,...,d-1\}\cup \{(n-1)d,...,nd-1\}} |G_{E,n}(\theta+k\omega; m-k, y)|\cdot \\
&\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\qquad\cdot \max_{\ell\in \{-d,...,d-1\}\cup \{(n-1)d,...,(n+1)d-1\}} |{u}_{k+\ell}|
\end{aligned}$$

# Bounding the denominator: Lemmas  <a href="#lem:detP" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:detP">15</a>, <a href="#lem:deno" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:deno">16</a>, <a href="#lem:fn_ave" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:fn_ave">18</a> and <a href="#lem:fn_upper" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:fn_upper">19</a>

