*Proof of Lemma <a href="#lem:detP" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:detP">15</a>.* This is implicit in the calculations of the previous section, cf. the upper left-hand corner of the block matrix of <a href="#eq:detS1B" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:detS1B">[eq:detS1B]</a>. For more details, see \*Lemma 5.1. ◻

</div>

<div class="proof">

*Proof of Lemma <a href="#lem:fn_upper" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:fn_upper">19</a>.* Let $\{v_{j}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\}_{j=1}^{2d}$ be the set of normalized singular vectors of $M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)$ such that $$M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon) v_j^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)=\sigma_j(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)) \cdot w_j^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon).$$ Then $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:Mn_singular_decom}
    M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)=W_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)D_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)V_n^*(\theta+i\varepsilon),

\end{aligned}$$ where $D_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)=\mathrm{diag}(\sigma_j(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))_{j=1}^{2d}$ and $V_n,W_n$ are the matrices with columns $v_j^{(n)}$ and $w_j^{(n)}$ respectively. By Hadamard’s inequality, $$\begin{aligned}
        |\det(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)-I_{2d})|=|\det (D_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)-W_n^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)V_n(\theta+i\varepsilon))|\leq \prod_{j=1}^{2d}\|r_j^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\|,

\end{aligned}$$ where $D_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)=\mathrm{diag}(\sigma_j(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))_{j=1}^{2d}$ and $V_n,W_n$ are the matrices with columns $v_j^{(n)}$ and $w_j^{(n)}$ respectively. By Hadamard’s inequality, $$\begin{aligned}
        |\det(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)-I_{2d})|=|\det (D_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)-W_n^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)V_n(\theta+i\varepsilon))|\leq \prod_{j=1}^{2d}\|r_j^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\|,

\end{aligned}$$ where $r_j^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)$ is the $j$-th column of $D_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)-W_n^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)V_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)$. Clearly $$\|r_j^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\|\leq \sigma_j(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))+1,$$ which implies $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:detM-I_upper}
        |\det(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)-I_{2d})|
        \leq &\prod_{j=1}^{2d}(\sigma_j(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))+1) \notag\\
        =&\sum_{k=1}^{2d}\, \sum_{1\leq j_1<...<j_{k}\leq 2d}\,\, \prod_{\ell=1}^{k} \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))+1.

\end{aligned}$$ where $r_j^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)$ is the $j$-th column of $D_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)-W_n^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)V_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)$. Clearly $$\|r_j^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\|\leq \sigma_j(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))+1,$$ which implies $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:detM-I_upper}
        |\det(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)-I_{2d})|
        \leq &\prod_{j=1}^{2d}(\sigma_j(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))+1) \notag\\
        =&\sum_{k=1}^{2d}\, \sum_{1\leq j_1<...<j_{k}\leq 2d}\,\, \prod_{\ell=1}^{k} \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))+1.

\end{aligned}$$ Let $\varepsilon_1=L_d(\omega,M_E)/4$. Then for $n$ large enough, and uniformly in $|\varepsilon|\leq \eta$ and $1\leq k\leq 2d$ one has $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:Lkn-Ln_eps1}
    L^k_{(n),\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)\leq L^k_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+\varepsilon_1.
\end{aligned}$$ Combining Lemma <a href="#lem:upperbd" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:upperbd">9</a> with <a href="#eq:Lkn-Ln_eps1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:Lkn-Ln_eps1">[eq:Lkn-Ln_eps1]</a>, we have for $n$ large enough, for any $1\leq k\leq 2d$, $k\neq d$, uniformly in $\theta$ that $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:prod_sigma_1}
    \prod_{\ell=1}^k \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\leq \prod_{\ell=1}^k \sigma_{\ell}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))
    \leq e^{n(L^k_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+\varepsilon_1)}.
\end{aligned}$$ For $k=d$, and $(j_1,...,j_d)\neq (1,...,d)$, one has (see ) that $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:prod_sigma_2}
\prod_{\ell=1}^d \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\leq e^{n(\max_{k\neq d} L^k_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+\varepsilon_1)}.
\end{aligned}$$ In fact if $\sigma_{j_d}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))<1$, then $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:prod_sigma_21}
    \prod_{\ell=1}^d \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\leq 
    \prod_{\ell=1}^{d-1} \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\leq e^{n(L^{d-1}_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+\varepsilon_1)},
\end{aligned}$$ where we applied <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_1">[eq:prod_sigma_1]</a> in the last inequality. If $\sigma_{j_d}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\geq 1$, then $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:prod_sigma_22}
    \prod_{\ell=1}^d \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\leq 
    \prod_{\ell=1}^{j_d} \sigma_{{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\leq e^{n(\max_{k\neq d} L^{k}_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+\varepsilon_1)},
\end{aligned}$$ where we applied <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_1">[eq:prod_sigma_1]</a> and noted that $j_d>d$. Combining <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_21" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_21">[eq:prod_sigma_21]</a> with <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_22" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_22">[eq:prod_sigma_22]</a> yields <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_2">[eq:prod_sigma_2]</a>.

\end{aligned}$$ Let $\varepsilon_1=L_d(\omega,M_E)/4$. Then for $n$ large enough, and uniformly in $|\varepsilon|\leq \eta$ and $1\leq k\leq 2d$ one has $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:Lkn-Ln_eps1}
    L^k_{(n),\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)\leq L^k_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+\varepsilon_1.
\end{aligned}$$ Combining Lemma <a href="#lem:upperbd" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:upperbd">9</a> with <a href="#eq:Lkn-Ln_eps1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:Lkn-Ln_eps1">[eq:Lkn-Ln_eps1]</a>, we have for $n$ large enough, for any $1\leq k\leq 2d$, $k\neq d$, uniformly in $\theta$ that $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:prod_sigma_1}
    \prod_{\ell=1}^k \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\leq \prod_{\ell=1}^k \sigma_{\ell}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))
    \leq e^{n(L^k_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+\varepsilon_1)}.
\end{aligned}$$ For $k=d$, and $(j_1,...,j_d)\neq (1,...,d)$, one has (see ) that $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:prod_sigma_2}
\prod_{\ell=1}^d \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\leq e^{n(\max_{k\neq d} L^k_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+\varepsilon_1)}.
\end{aligned}$$ In fact if $\sigma_{j_d}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))<1$, then $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:prod_sigma_21}
    \prod_{\ell=1}^d \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\leq 
    \prod_{\ell=1}^{d-1} \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\leq e^{n(L^{d-1}_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+\varepsilon_1)},
\end{aligned}$$ where we applied <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_1">[eq:prod_sigma_1]</a> in the last inequality. If $\sigma_{j_d}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\geq 1$, then $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:prod_sigma_22}
    \prod_{\ell=1}^d \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\leq 
    \prod_{\ell=1}^{j_d} \sigma_{{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\leq e^{n(\max_{k\neq d} L^{k}_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+\varepsilon_1)},
\end{aligned}$$ where we applied <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_1">[eq:prod_sigma_1]</a> and noted that $j_d>d$. Combining <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_21" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_21">[eq:prod_sigma_21]</a> with <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_22" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_22">[eq:prod_sigma_22]</a> yields <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_2">[eq:prod_sigma_2]</a>.

Note for $|\varepsilon|\leq \eta$, by the choice of $\varepsilon_1$ and <a href="#eq:L_d&gt;0_varepsilon" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:L_d&gt;0_varepsilon">[eq:L_d&gt;0_varepsilon]</a>, we have $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:prod_sigma_3}
    L^d_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)-\max_{k\neq d}(L^k_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+\varepsilon_1)\geq\frac{1}{4}L_d(\omega,M_E).
\end{aligned}$$ Therefore, combining <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_1">[eq:prod_sigma_1]</a> and <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_2">[eq:prod_sigma_2]</a> with <a href="#eq:detM-I_upper" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:detM-I_upper">[eq:detM-I_upper]</a>, yields $$\begin{aligned}
    |\det(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)-I_{2d})|
    \leq &\|\textstyle{\bigwedge}^d M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\|+C_d e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)-\frac{1}{4}L_d(\omega,M_E))}\\
    \leq &e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+n^{-\delta})}+C_d e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)-\frac{1}{4}L_d(\omega,M_E))}\\
    \leq &2e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_E)+n^{-\delta})},
\end{aligned}$$ in which we applied Lemma <a href="#lem:upperbd" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:upperbd">9</a> to bound $\|\textstyle{\bigwedge}^d M_{n,E}(\cdot+i\varepsilon)\|$. The claimed result follows from combining the above with $$\prod_{j=0}^{n-1}|\det B_j|\leq e^{n(\langle\log |B(\cdot+i\varepsilon)|\rangle+n^{-\delta'})},$$ for some $\delta'>\delta>0$ by the Diophantine property $\omega\in \mathrm{DC}$. ◻

</div>

Note that <a href="#eq:LDT_MN1_before" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:LDT_MN1_before">[eq:LDT_MN1_before]</a> provides us with a lower bound for $u_{N_1,\kappa}$, up to a set of measure $e^{-N_0^{\delta}/2}$, needed in the Cartan estimate. We still need an uniform upper bound in a neighborhood of $\mathbb T^b$. Applying Lemmas <a href="#lem:upperbd" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:upperbd">9</a> and <a href="#lem:Ln-L" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:Ln-L">13</a> to the cocycle $(\omega, M_E(\cdot+i\varepsilon+i\varepsilon'))$, implies uniformly in $\theta$ that $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:MM_upper1}
    \sup_{|\varepsilon'|\leq N_1^{-1}}\log \|\textstyle{\bigwedge}^d M_{N_1,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon+i\varepsilon')\|
    \leq &N_1 \sup_{|\varepsilon'|\leq N_1^{-1}} L^d_{\varepsilon+\varepsilon'}+N_1^{1-\delta}\notag\\
    \leq &N_1 (L^d_{\varepsilon}+Cb N_1^{-1})+N_1^{1-\delta},
\end{aligned}$$ where we used by Lemma <a href="#lem:Lip_eps" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:Lip_eps">11</a> that for $|\varepsilon'|\leq N_1^{-1}$, $$|L^d_{\varepsilon+\varepsilon'}-L^d_{\varepsilon}|\leq CbN_1^{-1}.$$ Clearly, <a href="#eq:MM_upper1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:MM_upper1">[eq:MM_upper1]</a> implies $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:MM_upper2}
    \sup_{|\varepsilon'|\leq N_1^{-1}}\log \|\textstyle{\bigwedge}^d \left(M_{N_1,E}(\theta+N_1\omega+\kappa+i\varepsilon+i\varepsilon') M_{N_1,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon+i\varepsilon')\right)\|
    \leq 2N_1 L^d_{\varepsilon}+3N_1^{1-\delta}.
\end{aligned}$$ We then have an upper bound of size $2N_1L^d_{\varepsilon}+3N_1^{1-\delta}$ for $u_{N_1,\kappa}(\theta+i\varepsilon)$ needed for the Cartan estimate. Applying Lemma <a href="#lem:Cartan" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:Cartan">22</a> with $K_1=2N_1L^d_{\varepsilon}+3N_1^{1-\delta}$, $m_1=2N_1L^d_{\varepsilon}-3N_1^{1-\delta}$ and $H_1=N_1^{\delta/2}$ (we actually cover $\mathbb T^b$ by polydisks with radius $N_1^{-1}$, and apply Cartan to each of the polydisk. Note that $N_1^{-1}>e^{-N_0^{\delta}/2}$ hence within each such polydisk there is a lower bound $m_1$), we have the following.

<div id="eq:LDT_M2_N1" class="lemma">

**Lemma 24**. *For any $|\kappa|\leq \kappa_0$ and any $N_1$ such that $4N_0<N_1\leq e^{N_0^{\delta/2}}$, the following holds $$\begin{aligned}
    \mathrm{mes}\left(\left\{\theta\in \mathbb T^b: u_{N_1,\kappa}(\theta+i\varepsilon)<2N_1L^d_{\varepsilon}-C_b N_1^{1-\frac{\delta}{2}}\right\}\right)<C_b e^{-N_1^{\delta/2}},
\end{aligned}$$ for some constant $C_b>0$ depending on $b$ only.*

</div>

Next, we perform the induction scheme. For $j\geq 1$, we fix an $N_j$ such that $N_j\in [e^{N_{j-1}^{\delta/4}}/4, e^{N_{j-1}^{\delta/4}}]$, and consider an arbitrary $N_{j+1}\in [4N_j, e^{N_j^{\delta/4}}]$. By decomposing monodromy matrices of size $2N_{j+1}$ into blocks of sizes $\simeq N_j$, and arguing as above, we have a lower bound of size $m_{j+1}=2N_{j+1}L^d_{\varepsilon}-3N_{j+1}^{1-\delta}$ for $$u_{N_{j+1},\kappa}(\theta+i\varepsilon):=\log \|\textstyle{\bigwedge}^d \left(M_{N_{j+1},E}(\theta+N_{j+1}\omega+\kappa+i\varepsilon) M_{N_{j+1},E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\right)\|,$$ up to a set of measure $e^{-N_j^{\delta/2}/2}$. We also have the upper bound $$\begin{aligned}
\sup_{|\varepsilon'|\leq N_{j+1}^{-1}} u_{N_{j+1},\kappa}(\theta+i\varepsilon+i\varepsilon')\leq 2N_{j+1}L^d_{\varepsilon}+3N_{j+1}^{1-\delta}=:K_{j+1}.
\end{aligned}$$ Cartan’s estimate (Lemma <a href="#lem:Cartan" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:Cartan">22</a>) with $H_{j+1}=N_{j+1}^{\delta/2}$, therefore implies

<div class="lemma">

*Proof.* Towards a contradiction, suppose that for some $\theta\in (\tilde{\mathcal{B}}_{n,E,\varepsilon})^c$ one has $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:assume_a1-d_small}
|\det (\langle v_{j}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon), w_{k}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\rangle)_{1\leq j,k\leq d}|\leq e^{-6n^{1-\delta_3}}.
\end{aligned}$$ For any $1\leq m_1<...<m_d\leq 2d$, we expand $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:wedge_w=wedge_v}
    w_{m_1}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\textstyle{\bigwedge}\cdots\textstyle{\bigwedge} w_{m_d}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)=\sum_{1\leq j_1<...<j_d\leq 2d} a^{j_1,...,j_d}_{m_1,...,m_d}(\theta+i\varepsilon) \cdot v_{j_1}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\textstyle{\bigwedge}\cdots\textstyle{\bigwedge} v_{j_d}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon),
\end{aligned}$$ in which $$\begin{aligned}
    a^{j_1,...,j_d}_{m_1,...,m_d}(\theta+i\varepsilon)=\langle w_{m_1}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\textstyle{\bigwedge}\cdots\textstyle{\bigwedge}  w_{m_d}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon), v_{j_1}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\textstyle{\bigwedge}\cdots\textstyle{\bigwedge}  v_{j_d}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\rangle.
\end{aligned}$$ For arbitrary $1\leq m_1<...<m_d\leq 2d$ and $1\leq j_1<...<j_d\leq 2d$, there is the trivial bound $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:aj1-jd_trivial}
    |a^{j_1,...,j_d}_{m_1,...,m_d}(\theta+i\varepsilon)|\leq 1.
\end{aligned}$$ By assumption <a href="#eq:assume_a1-d_small" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:assume_a1-d_small">[eq:assume_a1-d_small]</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:a1-d}
    |a_{1,...,d}^{1,...,d}(\theta+i\varepsilon)|\leq e^{-6n^{1-\delta_3}}.
\end{aligned}$$

By Lemmas <a href="#lem:upperbd" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:upperbd">9</a>, <a href="#lem:Ln-L" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:Ln-L">13</a>, and estimates <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_1">[eq:prod_sigma_1]</a>, <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_2">[eq:prod_sigma_2]</a>, <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_3" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_3">[eq:prod_sigma_3]</a>, <a href="#eq:aj1-jd_trivial" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:aj1-jd_trivial">[eq:aj1-jd_trivial]</a>, <a href="#eq:a1-d" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:a1-d">[eq:a1-d]</a>, one has for $n$ large enough, $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:M2_v1-d}
    \qquad &\|(\textstyle{\bigwedge}^d M_{n,E}^2(\theta+i\varepsilon)) (v_{1}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\textstyle{\bigwedge} \cdots \textstyle{\bigwedge} v_{d}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\|\notag\\
=&\prod_{j=1}^d \sigma_j(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\cdot  \|(\textstyle{\bigwedge}^d M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon) (w_{1}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\textstyle{\bigwedge}\cdots \textstyle{\bigwedge} w_{d}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\| \notag\\
\leq &e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}+2n^{-\delta})} \sum_{1\leq j_1<...<j_d\leq 2d} |a^{j_1,...,j_d}_{1,...,d}(\theta+i\varepsilon)|\cdot \prod_{\ell=1}^d \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\notag\\
=&e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}+2n^{-\delta})} \cdot \left(|a_{1,...,d}^{1,...,d}(\theta+i\varepsilon)|\cdot \prod_{j=1}^d\sigma_j(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\right.\\
&\qquad\qquad\qquad\left.+\sum_{(j_1,...,j_d)\neq (1,...,d)} |a^{j_1,...,j_d}_{1,...,d}(\theta+i\varepsilon)|\cdot \prod_{\ell=1}^d\sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\right)\notag\\
\leq &e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}+2n^{-\delta})} \cdot \left(e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}-4n^{-\delta_3})}+C_d \cdot e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}-\frac{1}{4}L_{d,\varepsilon})}\right)\notag\\
\leq &e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}-n^{-\delta_3})}.
\end{aligned}$$ For any $(m_1,...,m_d)\neq (1,...,d)$, we have similarly, $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:M2_vm1-md}
        &\|(\textstyle{\bigwedge}^d M_{n,E}^2(\theta+i\varepsilon)) (v_{m_1}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\textstyle{\bigwedge} \cdots \textstyle{\bigwedge} v_{m_d}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\|\notag\\
=&\prod_{\ell=1}^d \sigma_{m_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)) \cdot \|(\textstyle{\bigwedge}^d M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon) (w_{m_1}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\textstyle{\bigwedge}\cdots \textstyle{\bigwedge} w_{m_d}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\| \notag\\
\leq &e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}-\frac{1}{4}L_{d,\varepsilon})} \sum_{1\leq j_1<...<j_d\leq 2d} |a^{j_1,...,j_d}_{m_1,...,m_d}(\theta+i\varepsilon)|\cdot \prod_{\ell=1}^d \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\notag\\
=&e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}-\frac{1}{4}L_{d,\varepsilon})} \cdot \left(\prod_{j=1}^d\sigma_j(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))+\sum_{(j_1,...,j_d)\neq (1,...,d)} \prod_{\ell=1}^d\sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\right)\notag\\
\leq &e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}-\frac{1}{4}L_{d,\varepsilon})} \cdot \left(e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}+2n^{-\delta})}+C_d \cdot e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}-\frac{1}{4}L_{d,\varepsilon})}\right)\notag\\
\leq &e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}-\frac{1}{8}L_{d,\varepsilon})}.
\end{aligned}$$ Combining <a href="#eq:M2_v1-d" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:M2_v1-d">[eq:M2_v1-d]</a> with <a href="#eq:M2_vm1-md" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:M2_vm1-md">[eq:M2_vm1-md]</a>, we arrive at a contradiction with $\theta\in (\tilde{\mathcal{B}}_{n,E,\varepsilon})^c$. ◻

Now we are in position to complete the proof of Lemma <a href="#lem:deno" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:deno">16</a>.

The singular value decomposition of $M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)$ yields $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:M=DWV}
    |\det(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)-I_{2d})|=|\det (D_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)-W_{n}^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)V_{n}(\theta+i\varepsilon))|.
\end{aligned}$$ Note that $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:WV=Q}
    W_{n}^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)V_{n}(\theta+i\varepsilon)
    =&\left(\begin{matrix} (w_{1}^{(n)})^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)\\ \vdots\\ (w_{2d}^{(n)})^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)\end{matrix}\right)\cdot (v_{1}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon),...,v_{2d}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\notag\\
    =&
    \left(\langle w_{j}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon), v_{k}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\rangle\right)_{1\leq j,k\leq 2d}
    =:Q_n(\theta+i\varepsilon).
\end{aligned}$$ Hence, $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:D-UU}
\qquad &|\det(D_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)-W_{n}^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)V_{n}(\theta+i\varepsilon))|\\
\leq &|\det(-Q_n(\theta+i\varepsilon))|\\
&+\sum_{k=1}^{2d}\,\, \sum_{1\leq j_1<...<j_k\leq 2d}\,\, \prod_{\ell=1}^k \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\cdot \left|\det (Q_n(\theta+i\varepsilon))_{\{1,...,2d\}\setminus \{j_1,...,j_k\}, \{1,...,2d\}\setminus \{j_1,...,j_k\}}\right|,
\end{aligned}$$ in which, for a matrix $M$, $M_{B_1,B_2}$ refers to the submatrix with row numbers in the set $B_1$ and column numbers taken from the set $B_2$. By Hadamard’s inequality, $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:detQ_0}
|\det Q_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)|\leq \prod_{\ell=1}^{2d} \|(Q_n(\theta+i\varepsilon))_{\ell}\|\leq 1,
\end{aligned}$$ and $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:detQ_1}
    \left|\det (Q_n(\theta+i\varepsilon))_{\{1,...,2d\}\setminus \{j_1,...,j_k\}, \{1,...,2d\}\setminus \{j_1,...,j_k\}}\right|\leq \prod_{\ell\notin \{j_1,..,j_k\}} \| (Q_n(\theta+i\varepsilon))_{\ell}\|\leq 1
\end{aligned}$$ where $(Q_n(\theta+i\varepsilon))_{\ell}$ refers to the $\ell$-th column of $Q_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)$. Moreover, we used the following bound $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:Q<1}
    \| (Q_n(\theta+i\varepsilon))_{\ell}\|\leq \|v_{\ell}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\|=1.
\end{aligned}$$ Corollary <a href="#cor:det_vd+1_2d_w" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="cor:det_vd+1_2d_w">27</a> implies that $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:detQ_2}
    &\left|\det (Q_n(\theta+i\varepsilon))_{\{d+1,...,2d\}, \{d+1,...,2d\}}\right|\\
=& \left|\langle w_{d+1}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\textstyle{\bigwedge}\cdots \textstyle{\bigwedge} w_{2d}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon), v_{d+1}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\textstyle{\bigwedge} \cdots \textstyle{\bigwedge} v_{2d}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)\rangle\right|
\geq e^{-6n^{1-\delta_3}}.
\end{aligned}$$ Combining the estimates <a href="#eq:detQ_0" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:detQ_0">[eq:detQ_0]</a>, <a href="#eq:detQ_1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:detQ_1">[eq:detQ_1]</a>, <a href="#eq:detQ_2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:detQ_2">[eq:detQ_2]</a>, <a href="#eq:D-UU" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:D-UU">[eq:D-UU]</a> with <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_1">[eq:prod_sigma_1]</a>, <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_2">[eq:prod_sigma_2]</a> and <a href="#eq:prod_sigma_3" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:prod_sigma_3">[eq:prod_sigma_3]</a>, we infer that for $\theta\in (\tilde{\mathcal{B}}_{n,E,\varepsilon})^c\cap (\mathcal{B}_{n,E,\varepsilon})^c$ $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:detM-I}
    |\det( M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)-I_{2d})|
\geq &\prod_{j=1}^d \sigma_j(M_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)) \cdot e^{-6n^{1-\delta_3}}-C_d\, \sup_{k=0,\ldots,2d}\, \sup_{\substack{1\leq j_1<...<j_k\leq 2d\\ (j_1,...,j_k)\neq (1,...,d)}}\, \prod_{\ell=1}^k \sigma_{j_{\ell}}(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon))
\\ 
\geq &e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}-7n^{-\delta_3})}-C_d\, e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}-\frac{1}{4}L_{d,\varepsilon})}\\
\geq &e^{n(L^d_{\varepsilon}-8n^{-\delta_3})}.
\end{aligned}$$ The claimed result follows from combining the above with the following large deviation estimate $$\mathrm{mes}\left\{\theta\in \mathbb T^b: \left|\frac{1}{n}\sum_{j=0}^{n-1}\log |\det (B(\theta+j\omega+i\varepsilon))|-\langle \log |\det B(\cdot+i\varepsilon)|\rangle\right|>n^{-\delta'}\right\}<e^{-n^{\delta'}}$$ which holds for some $\delta'>0$ due to $\omega\in \mathrm{DC}$. Thus we have completed the proof of Lemma <a href="#lem:deno" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:deno">16</a>. ◻

The singular value decomposition of $M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)$ yields $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:M=DWV}
    |\det(M_{n,E}(\theta+i\varepsilon)-I_{2d})|=|\det (D_n(\theta+i\varepsilon)-W_{n}^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)V_{n}(\theta+i\varepsilon))|.
\end{aligned}$$ Note that $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:WV=Q}
    W_{n}^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)V_{n}(\theta+i\varepsilon)
    =&\left(\begin{matrix} (w_{1}^{(n)})^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)\\ \vdots\\ (w_{2d}^{(n)})^*(\theta+i\varepsilon)\end{matrix}\right)\cdot (v_{1}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon),...,v_{2d}^{(n)}(\theta+i\varepsilon))\notag\\
    =&
