*Proof.* First note that if $\omega\in \mathrm{DC}_{a,A}$, then for any $k\in \mathbb Z\setminus \{0\}$ $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:domega_Dio}
    \|kd^{-1}\omega\|_{\mathbb T}\geq \frac{a}{d |k|^{A}}.
\end{aligned}$$ Suppose otherwise, we have for some $k_0\neq 0$ that $$\begin{aligned}
|k_0d^{-1}\omega-p|<\frac{a}{d|k_0|^A}
\end{aligned}$$ for some $p\in \mathbb Z$, which implies $\|k_0\omega\|_{\mathbb T}\leq |k_0\omega-dp|<\frac{a}{|k_0|^A}$ contradicting $\omega\in \mathrm{DC}_{a,A}$.

Next, note that the cardinality $$\begin{aligned}
\# I_1+\# I_2\geq \frac{3}{2} nd-2> n(d+\nu)\geq N,
\end{aligned}$$ for $n$ large enough. It then suffices to prove that each pair $U_j\cup (-(nd-1)d^{-1}\omega-U_j)$ consists of at most one point in $\{\theta+\ell d^{-1}\omega\}_{\ell\in I_1\cup I_2}$. Arguing by contradiction, suppose there exist $\ell_1, \ell_2$ such that $$\begin{aligned}
\theta+\ell_1 d^{-1}\omega\in U_j, \text{ and } \theta+\ell_2 d^{-1}\omega\in U_j.
\end{aligned}$$ Then by <a href="#eq:domega_Dio" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:domega_Dio">[eq:domega_Dio]</a> and that $|\ell_1-\ell_2|<11nd$, $$\begin{aligned}
|U_j|\geq \|\theta+\ell_1 d^{-1}\omega-(\theta+\ell_2 d^{-1}\omega)\|_{\mathbb T}=\|(\ell_1-\ell_2)d^{-1}\omega\|_{\mathbb T}\geq \frac{a}{d(11nd)^A}>e^{-n^{\delta_1/2}},
\end{aligned}$$ contradicting Lemma <a href="#lem:complexity_1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:complexity_1">39</a>. The case when $$\begin{aligned}
\theta+\ell_1d^{-1}\omega\in (-(nd-1)d^{-1}\omega-U_j), \text{ and } \theta+\ell_2d^{-1}\omega\in (-(nd-1)d^{-1}\omega-U_j). 
\end{aligned}$$ is similar. In fact, suppose there exist $\ell_1, \ell_2$ such that $$\begin{aligned}
\theta+\ell_1d^{-1}\omega\in U_j, \text{ and } \theta+\ell_2d^{-1}\omega\in (-(nd-1)d^{-1}\omega-U_j). 
\end{aligned}$$ Since $\theta\in (\Theta_d)^c$, there exists $a'>0$ and $t>1$ such that for $k\in d^{-1}\mathbb Z$ large enough, one has $$\begin{aligned}
\|2\theta+k\omega\|_{\mathbb T}\geq \frac{a'}{|k|^t}.
\end{aligned}$$ Using that $-3nd/4\leq \ell_1+\ell_2+nd\leq 11nd$, we infer that $$\begin{aligned}
|U_j|\geq &\|\theta+\ell_1d^{-1}\omega-(-\theta-\ell_2d^{-1}\omega-(nd-1)d^{-1}\omega\|_{\mathbb T}\\
=&\|2\theta+(\ell_1+\ell_2+nd-1)d^{-1}\omega\|_{\mathbb T}\geq \frac{a'}{(11n)^{t}}\geq e^{-n^{\delta_1/2}}.
\end{aligned}$$ This contradicts with Lemma <a href="#lem:complexity_1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:complexity_1">39</a> again. Thus the claimed results hold. ◻

