<div id="lem:I1_small" class="lemma">

**Lemma 42**. *Under the same conditions as Lemma <a href="#lem:I1_I2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:I1_I2">41</a>. For any $\ell\in I_1$, one has $\theta+\ell d^{-1}\omega\in \bigcup_{j=1}^{N}(U_j\cup (-(nd-1)d^{-1}\omega-U_j))$.*

</div>

<div class="proof">

*Proof.* Argue by contradiction. Suppose there exists $\ell_1\in I_1$ such that $$\theta+\ell_1\alpha\notin \bigcup_{j=1}^{N}(U_j\cup (-(nd-1)d^{-1}\omega-U_j)).$$ By Lemma <a href="#lem:complexity_1" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:complexity_1">39</a>, it is necessary that $\theta+\ell_1d^{-1}\omega\notin \widetilde{\mathcal{B}}_{f,n,E}$, which implies $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:u_I1_large}
\frac{1}{n}\log |f_{E,n}(\theta+\ell_1d^{-1}\omega)|\geq L^d+\log |\det B|-n^{-\delta_1/2}.
\end{aligned}$$ Let $\ell_2:=\ell_1+nd-1$. By Lemma <a href="#lem:numerator" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:numerator">14</a>, for any $\varepsilon_1>0$, we see that for $n$ large enough, $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:Dk_upper}
&\sup_{m\in \{0,...,d-1\}}\max(\log |\mu_{n,m,-\ell_1}(\theta+\ell_1d^{-1}\omega)|, \log |\mu_{n,nd-1-m,-\ell_1}(\theta+\ell_1 d^{-1}\omega)|)\\
&\qquad\qquad \leq n\cdot \log |\det B|+\max(-[\ell_1d^{-1}] L^{d-1}+[\ell_2d^{-1}] L^d, -[\ell_1d^{-1}] L^d+[\ell_2d^{-1}] L^{d-1})+n\varepsilon_1
\end{aligned}$$ This implies by <a href="#eq:mufn" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:mufn">[eq:mufn]</a> that for any $m\in \{0,...,d-1\}$, $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:Green_I1}
    |G_{E,n}(\theta+\ell_1d^{-1}\omega; -\ell_1, m)|=&\frac{|\mu_{n,m,-\ell_1}(\theta+\ell_1d^{-1}\omega)|}{|f_{E,n}(\theta+\ell_1d^{-1}\omega)|}\leq \max(e^{[\ell_1d^{-1}]L_d}, e^{-[\ell_2d^{-1}] L_d})\cdot  e^{n\varepsilon_1}\\
    |G_{E,n}(\theta+\ell_1d^{-1}\omega; -\ell_1, nd-1-m)=&\frac{|\mu_{n,nd-1-m,-\ell_1}(\theta+\ell_1d^{-1}\omega)|}{|f_{E,n}(\theta+\ell_1d^{-1}\omega)|}\leq \max(e^{[\ell_1d^{-1}] L_d}, e^{-[\ell_2d^{-1}] L_d})\cdot  e^{n\varepsilon_1}.
\end{aligned}$$ Combining the above with <a href="#eq:Poisson_exp" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:Poisson_exp">[eq:Poisson_exp]</a> and <a href="#eq:Schnol" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:Schnol">[eq:Schnol]</a>, we have $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:phi0}
|u_0|
\leq C\sum_{k\in \{0,...,d-1\}\cup \{(n-1)d,...,nd-1\}}\max(e^{[\ell_1d^{-1}] L_d}, e^{-[\ell_2d^{-1}] L_d})\cdot  e^{n\varepsilon_1} \cdot (nd)
\leq e^{-\frac{1}{10} n L_d}.
\end{aligned}$$ invoking $\min(|\ell_1|, |\ell_2|)\geq [nd/8]$. Similarly, one shows that $|u_1|<1/2$. Hence we arrive at a contradiction with the assumption that $\max(|u_0|, |u_1|)=1$. ◻

