\end{aligned}$$ where $\omega\in \mathbb T^b$ is the frequency, $\theta\in \mathbb T^b$ is the phase and the potential $v$ is assumed to be a non-constant analytic function on $\mathbb T^b$. The underlying Hilbert space is $\mathcal{H}=\bigotimes_{j=1}^n\mathbb C^2$. The matrices $\sigma^x, \sigma^y, \sigma^z$ are the Pauli matrices given by $$\begin{aligned}
\sigma^x=\left(\begin{matrix}
0 \ &1\\
1 &0
\end{matrix}\right),\,
\sigma^y=\left(\begin{matrix}
0 \ &-i\\
i &0
\end{matrix}\right),
\text{ and }
\sigma^z=\left(\begin{matrix}
1 \ &0\\
0 &-1
\end{matrix}\right),
\end{aligned}$$ and $\sigma_j^x$ etc. means that the Pauli matrix acts on the $j^{th}$ component of the tensorial state. It is well-known that the XY-chain models can be reduced to the following Hamiltonian $\widetilde{H}^{XY}_{n,\omega,\theta,\rho,v}$ of the free Fermions via the Jordan-Wigner transformation (see e.g. ): $$\label{def:tH_XY}
\widetilde{H}^{XY}_{n,\omega,\theta,\rho,v}=\left( \begin{array}{ccccc} V(\theta+n\omega) & B^* & & & \\ B & V(\theta+(n-1)\omega) & \ddots & & \\ & \ddots & \ddots & \ddots & \\ & & \ddots & \ddots & B^*\\ & & & B & V(\theta+\omega) \end{array} \right),$$ where $$\begin{aligned}
    B=\left(\begin{matrix}1 &\rho\\ -\rho &-1\end{matrix}\right), \text{ and } V(\theta)=\left(\begin{matrix} v(\theta) &0 \\ 0 &-v(\theta)\end{matrix}\right).
