It was shown by Hamza-Sims-Stolz that dynamical localization of the anisotropic XY-chain, characterized by the zero-velocity Lieb-Robinson bound, is equivalent to the exponential dynamical localization of $\widetilde{H}^{XY}_{n,\omega,\theta,\rho,v}$, viz. $$\begin{aligned}
E\left(\sup_{t\in \mathbb R} \left| (e^{-i t \widetilde{H}^{XY}_{n,\omega,\theta,\rho,v} })_{j,k}\right|\right)\leq C e^{-\eta |j-k|}
\end{aligned}$$ for all $n$ and $j,k\in [1,2n]$. Later it was proved in by Chapman-Stolz that dynamical localization holds for the anisotropic XY-chain with random magnetic fields at arbitrarily small disorder. Spin chains with deterministic magnetic fields are much less understood. For isotropic XY-chains with quasi-periodic magnetic fields, an interesting anomalous Lieb-Robinson bound was proved by Damanik-Lemm-Lukic-Yessen . Positive lower bounds of the Lieb-Robinson velocity were obtained by in the periodic setting. Moreover, they covered quasi-periodic models under a reducibility assumption, as well as the limit-periodic case. As far as the anisotropic case is concerned, the only results so far are by Damanik-Lukic-Yessen for periodic magnetic fields.

It was shown by Hamza-Sims-Stolz that dynamical localization of the anisotropic XY-chain, characterized by the zero-velocity Lieb-Robinson bound, is equivalent to the exponential dynamical localization of $\widetilde{H}^{XY}_{n,\omega,\theta,\rho,v}$, viz. $$\begin{aligned}
E\left(\sup_{t\in \mathbb R} \left| (e^{-i t \widetilde{H}^{XY}_{n,\omega,\theta,\rho,v} })_{j,k}\right|\right)\leq C e^{-\eta |j-k|}
\end{aligned}$$ for all $n$ and $j,k\in [1,2n]$. Later it was proved in by Chapman-Stolz that dynamical localization holds for the anisotropic XY-chain with random magnetic fields at arbitrarily small disorder. Spin chains with deterministic magnetic fields are much less understood. For isotropic XY-chains with quasi-periodic magnetic fields, an interesting anomalous Lieb-Robinson bound was proved by Damanik-Lemm-Lukic-Yessen . Positive lower bounds of the Lieb-Robinson velocity were obtained by in the periodic setting. Moreover, they covered quasi-periodic models under a reducibility assumption, as well as the limit-periodic case. As far as the anisotropic case is concerned, the only results so far are by Damanik-Lukic-Yessen for periodic magnetic fields.

In this paper, we study the infinite volume version of the anisotropic $\widetilde{H}_{n,\omega,\theta,\rho,v}^{XY}$ in the positve Lyapunov exponent regime, which complements the earlier studies. Thus, we define $$\begin{aligned}
(\widetilde{H}^{XY}_{\omega,\theta,\rho,v}\phi)_n=B \phi_{n+1}+V(\theta+n\omega) \phi_n+B^* \phi_{n-1},
\end{aligned}$$ where $$\begin{aligned}
    B=\left(\begin{matrix}1 &\rho\\ -\rho &-1\end{matrix}\right), \text{ and } V(\theta)=\left(\begin{matrix} v(\theta) &0 \\ 0 &-v(\theta)\end{matrix}\right).
\end{aligned}$$ Clearly this is a $2\times 2$ block-valued Jacobi matrix. As an immediate corollary of Theorem <a href="#thm:main" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:main">1</a>, one has:

<div id="cor:thm1_XY" class="corollary">

**Corollary 51**. *$\widetilde{H}^{XY}_{\omega,\theta=0,\rho,v}$ is Anderson localized in the positive Lyapunov exponent regime for a.e. $\omega\in \mathbb T^b$.*

</div>

We now restrict to the case of one-dimensional torus to address arithmetic Anderson localization.

## Skew-shift with rational frequencies

Let $\theta,y\in \mathbb T$. Let us consider the following operator on $\ell^2(\mathbb Z, \mathbb C^q)$: $$\begin{aligned}
\label{def:hatH_sk}
    (\widehat{H}_{\lambda,\theta,y,p/q}\hat{U})_k=B\, \hat{U}_{k+1}+B^* \hat{U}_{k-1}+V(\theta+ky)\hat{U}_{k},
\end{aligned}$$ where $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:V_sk}
    V(\theta)=
    \left(\begin{matrix}
        0 & e^{2\pi i \theta} & & &e^{-2\pi i\theta}\\
        e^{-2\pi i\theta} &0 &\ddots & &\\
        &\ddots &\ddots &\ddots &\\
        & &\ddots &\ddots &e^{2\pi i\theta}\\
        e^{2\pi i\theta}& & &e^{-2\pi i\theta} &0
    \end{matrix}\right)_{q\times q},
\end{aligned}$$ and $B\in \mathrm{Mat}(\mathbb C, q)$ be an arbitrary diagonal matrix. A particular choice of $B$ that is of interest to us is the following: $$\begin{aligned}
\label{def:Bsk}
    B_{sk}=\lambda\, \mathrm{diag}(e^{2\pi i j(j-1)p/q})_{j=q-1}^0,
\end{aligned}$$ with $p/q\in (0,1)$ being a reduced rational with $q\geq 3$. The specific choice of $B_{sk}$ arises from taking the dual model of the following Schrödinger operator $H^{sk}_{\lambda,x,y,p/q}$ on $\ell^2(\mathbb Z)$ with skew-shift dynamics with frequency $p/q$, see <a href="#def:skew_shift" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="def:skew_shift">[def:skew_shift]</a>: $$\begin{aligned}
    (H^{sk}_{\lambda,x,y,p/q}u)_n=u_{n+1}+u_{n-1}+2\lambda\cos(2\pi(x+ny+n(n-1)p/q)))u_n.
\end{aligned}$$ For any irrational $y$, the spectrum $\sigma(H^{sk}_{\lambda,x,y,p/q})$ is constant in $x$, and $\sigma(\widehat{H}_{\lambda,\theta,y,p/q})$ is constant in $\theta$. In the rest of this section, we will fix a $y\in \mathrm{DC}$.

The first goal of this section is to prove the almost localization of $\widehat{H}_{\lambda,\theta,y,p/q}$.

<div class="definition">

Clearly $|I_1|+|I_2|>\frac{9}{8}n-C$, for some absolute constant $C>0$. Also since $\kappa^q\leq q$ (see <a href="#eq:kappa_q=q" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:kappa_q=q">[eq:kappa_q=q]</a>), which is a tighter upper bound than $2q-1$, Lemma <a href="#lem:complexity_2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:complexity_2">47</a> implies $N\leq n(1+\varepsilon_1)$ for $\varepsilon_1\in (0,1/10)$. Since $|I_1|+|I_2|>N$, by the Pigeon hole principle, there exists $1\leq j\leq N$ and $\ell_1,\ell_2\in I_1\cup I_2$ such that $$\begin{aligned}
    \{\theta+\ell_1 y, \theta+\ell_2 y\}\subset \left(\bigcup_{m_1=1}^q (U_j+m_1/q)\right)\cup \left(\bigcup_{m_2=1}^q (-U_j-(n-1)y+m_2/q)\right)
\end{aligned}$$

It is clear that $y\in \mathrm{DC}_{a,A}$ and the measure estimate of $\mathrm{mes}(U_j)$ in Lemma <a href="#lem:complexity_2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:complexity_2">47</a> excludes the possibility of $$\begin{aligned}
    \{\theta+\ell_1 y, \theta+\ell_2 y\}\subset  \bigcup_{m_1=1}^q (U_j+m_1/q),
\end{aligned}$$ or $$\begin{aligned}
    \{\theta+\ell_1 y, \theta+\ell_2 y\}\subset  \bigcup_{m_2=1}^q (-U_j-(n-1)y+m_2/q)
\end{aligned}$$ It remains to consider the case when $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:assume_I1_I2_2'}
    \theta+\ell_1 y\in \bigcup_{m_1=1}^q (U_j+m_1/q), \text{ and } \theta+\ell_2 y\in \bigcup_{m_2=1}^q(-U_j-(n-1)y+m_2/q).
\end{aligned}$$ There exist $m_1,m_2\in \{1,...,d\}$ such that $$\begin{aligned}
    \theta+\ell_1 y-m_1/q\in U_j, \text{ and } -(\theta+(\ell_2+n-1)y- m_2/q)\in U_j.
\end{aligned}$$ Taking the difference, we obtain $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:Uj_contra_1}
    \mathrm{mes}(U_j)
    \geq &\|2\theta+(\ell_1+\ell_2+n-1)y-(m_1+m_2)/q\|_{\mathbb T} \notag\\
    \geq &q^{-1}\|q\cdot (2\theta+(\ell_1+\ell_2+n-1)y)\|_{\mathbb T}.
\end{aligned}$$ The key to estimate the term on the right-hand side of the equation above is to show: $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:I_1+I_2_neq_nj}
\ell_1+\ell_2+n-1\neq -n_j.   
\end{aligned}$$ We divide into two different cases, depending on if $n_j\geq 0$.

<u>Case 1</u>. If $n_j\geq 0$. Due to the choices of $I_1, I_2$ and $n$, one has $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:l1+l2_1}
    \ell_1+\ell_2+n-1\geq -n+n-1\geq -1>-n_j.
\end{aligned}$$

<u>Case 2.1</u>. If $n_j<0$ and $\ell_1,\ell_2\in I_1$, then $$\begin{aligned}
    \ell_1+\ell_2+n-1\leq -2[\frac{1}{2}n]+n-1\leq 1<-n_j.
\end{aligned}$$

### Proof of Theorem <a href="#thm:skew_shift" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:skew_shift">7</a>

The $2\times 2$ transfer matrix associated to $H^{sk}_{\lambda,x,y,p/q}$ along the skew-shift dynamics $$\begin{aligned}
\label{def:skew_shift}
T^{sk}_{p/q}(x,y)=(x+y, y+p/q)
\end{aligned}$$ is $$\begin{aligned}
    M^{\cos}_{E}(x):=\left(\begin{matrix}
        E-2\lambda\cos(2\pi x) &-1\\
        1 &0
    \end{matrix}\right).
\end{aligned}$$ Our goal is to show that if $|\lambda|>0$ is small enough, then for every $y\in \mathrm{DC}$, and every $E\in \sigma(H^{sk}_{\lambda,x,y,p/q})$, $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:zero_LE_goal}
    L^{sk}_{p/q}(E,y):=\lim_{\ell\to\infty} \frac{1}{\ell}\int_{\mathbb T} \log \|\prod_{m=\ell-1}^0 M_E^{\cos}(x+my+m(m-1)p/q)\|\, \mathrm{d}x=0.
\end{aligned}$$

To this end, we first show $L^{sk}_{p/q}(E,y)=0$ for every eigenvalue of $\widehat{H}_{\lambda,0,y,p/q}$ with $B=B_{sk}$ as in <a href="#def:Bsk" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="def:Bsk">[def:Bsk]</a>.

To this end, we first show $L^{sk}_{p/q}(E,y)=0$ for every eigenvalue of $\widehat{H}_{\lambda,0,y,p/q}$ with $B=B_{sk}$ as in <a href="#def:Bsk" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="def:Bsk">[def:Bsk]</a>.

Fix $\theta=0$ (one can also fix any non-resonant $\theta$). Clearly, for $y\in \mathrm{DC}$, $\theta=0$ is $\varepsilon$-non-resonant for any $\varepsilon>0$. Hence $n_{j+1}=\infty$ for some $j$. Theorem <a href="#thm:sk_dual_almost_AL" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:sk_dual_almost_AL">53</a> implies $\widehat{H}_{\lambda,0,y,p/q}$ has pure point spectrum with exponentially decaying eigenfunctions if $|\lambda|>0$ is small enough. Indeed the potential matrix $V$ as in <a href="#eq:V_sk" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:V_sk">[eq:V_sk]</a> does not have constant eigenvalue, hence by , $\widetilde{H}_{\lambda,\theta,y,p/q}$ has $q$ positive Lyapunov exponents, each of the order $\log (|\lambda|^{-1})+O(1)$. Fixing an arbitrary eigenvalue $E$ of $\widehat{H}_{\lambda,0,y,p/q}$, and let $\hat{U}$ be the corresponding normalized eigenfunction. Let $\hat{U}=(...,\hat{U}_{1}, \hat{U}_0, \hat{U}_{-1},...)^T$, where for each $k\in \mathbb Z$, $$\hat{U}_k=(\hat{u}_k^{(q-1)},...,\hat{u}_k^{(0)}).$$ For each $j\in \mathbb Z_q=\mathbb Z/(q\mathbb Z)$ and each $x\in \mathbb T$, let $u^{(j)}(x)=\sum_{k\in \mathbb Z} \hat{u}^{(j)}_k e^{-2\pi i kx}\in C^{\omega}(\mathbb T)$. We have for each $j\in \mathbb Z_q$, $$\begin{aligned}
    \lambda e^{2\pi i j(j-1)p/q} \hat{u}^{(j)}_{k+1}+\lambda e^{-2\pi i j(j-1)p/q} \hat{u}^{(j)}_{k-1}+e^{-2\pi i ky}\hat{u}^{(j+1)}_k+e^{2\pi i ky}\hat{u}^{(j-1)}_k=E\hat{u}^{(j)}_k,
\end{aligned}$$ This implies for any $x\in \mathbb T$ and $j\in \mathbb Z_q$ that $$\begin{aligned}
    2\lambda \cos(2\pi (x+j(j-1)p/q)) u^{(j)}(x)+u^{(j+1)}(x+y)+u^{(j-1)}(x-y)=Eu^{(j)}(x).
\end{aligned}$$ The above implies $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:Mb=b}
    M_{\lambda,E}^{\cos}(x+j(j-1)p/q)\cdot b_{j,y}(x)=b_{j+1,y}(x+y),
\end{aligned}$$ in which for $j\in \mathbb Z_q$, $$\begin{aligned}
    b_{j,y}(x):=\left(\begin{matrix} u^{(j)}(x)\\ u^{(j-1)}(x-y)\end{matrix}\right).
\end{aligned}$$ <a href="#eq:Mb=b" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:Mb=b">[eq:Mb=b]</a> implies for any $\ell\in \mathbb Z$ and $x\in \mathbb T$ that $$\begin{aligned}
    \prod_{m=\ell q-1}^{0}M_E^{\cos}(x+m y+m(m-1)p/q) \cdot b_{0, y}(x)=b_{0,y}(x+\ell q y).
\end{aligned}$$ We decompose $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:M_lq=tM_l}
    \prod_{m=\ell q-1}^{0}M_E^{\cos}(x+m y+m(m-1)p/q)
    =:\prod_{k=\ell-1}^{0} \widetilde{M}^{\cos}_{q,E,y,p/q}(x+kqy),
\end{aligned}$$ where $$\begin{aligned}
\widetilde{M}^{\cos}_{q,E,y,p/q}(x)=\prod_{m=q-1}^0 M_E^{\cos}(x+my+m(m-1)p/q).
\end{aligned}$$ Hence <a href="#eq:Mb=b" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:Mb=b">[eq:Mb=b]</a> implies for every $x\in \mathbb T$, $$\begin{aligned}
    \lim_{\ell\to\infty}\frac{1}{\ell}\log \|\prod_{k=\ell-1}^{0} \widetilde{M}^{\cos}_{q,E,y,p/q}(x+kqy)\cdot b_{0, y}(x)\|=0.
\end{aligned}$$ This implies via the Oseledets theorem, see \*Theorem 4.2, that $$\begin{aligned}
    \lim_{\ell\to\infty}\frac{1}{\ell}\int_{\mathbb T} \log \|\prod_{k=\ell-1}^{0} \widetilde{M}^{\cos}_{q,E,y,p/q}(x+kqy)\|\, \mathrm{d}x=0,
\end{aligned}$$ which, due to <a href="#eq:M_lq=tM_l" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:M_lq=tM_l">[eq:M_lq=tM_l]</a>, implies for every $y\in \mathrm{DC}$, $$\begin{aligned}
\label{def:LE_sk_y}
    L^{sk}_{p/q}(E,y):=\lim_{\ell\to\infty} \frac{1}{\ell}\int_{\mathbb T} \log \|\prod_{m=\ell-1}^0 M_E^{\cos}(x+my+m(m-1)p/q)\|\, \mathrm{d}x=0.
\end{aligned}$$ This implies $L^{sk}_{p/q}(E,y)=0$ on $\sigma(\widehat{H}_{\lambda,0,y,p/q})$, since eigenvalues of $\widehat{H}_{\lambda,0,y,p/q}$ form a dense set in $\sigma(\widehat{H}_{\lambda,0,y,p/q})$, and $L^{sk}_{p/q}(E,y)$ is a sub-harmonic function, hence upper semi-continuous in $E$. Finally it suffices to show $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:claimed_dual}
\sigma(\widehat{H}_{\lambda,\theta,y,p/q})=\sigma(H^{sk}_{\lambda,x,y,p/q})
\end{aligned}$$ for any irrational $y$ and any $x,\theta\in \mathbb T$.

Fix $\theta=0$ (one can also fix any non-resonant $\theta$). Clearly, for $y\in \mathrm{DC}$, $\theta=0$ is $\varepsilon$-non-resonant for any $\varepsilon>0$. Hence $n_{j+1}=\infty$ for some $j$. Theorem <a href="#thm:sk_dual_almost_AL" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:sk_dual_almost_AL">53</a> implies $\widehat{H}_{\lambda,0,y,p/q}$ has pure point spectrum with exponentially decaying eigenfunctions if $|\lambda|>0$ is small enough. Indeed the potential matrix $V$ as in <a href="#eq:V_sk" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:V_sk">[eq:V_sk]</a> does not have constant eigenvalue, hence by , $\widetilde{H}_{\lambda,\theta,y,p/q}$ has $q$ positive Lyapunov exponents, each of the order $\log (|\lambda|^{-1})+O(1)$. Fixing an arbitrary eigenvalue $E$ of $\widehat{H}_{\lambda,0,y,p/q}$, and let $\hat{U}$ be the corresponding normalized eigenfunction. Let $\hat{U}=(...,\hat{U}_{1}, \hat{U}_0, \hat{U}_{-1},...)^T$, where for each $k\in \mathbb Z$, $$\hat{U}_k=(\hat{u}_k^{(q-1)},...,\hat{u}_k^{(0)}).$$ For each $j\in \mathbb Z_q=\mathbb Z/(q\mathbb Z)$ and each $x\in \mathbb T$, let $u^{(j)}(x)=\sum_{k\in \mathbb Z} \hat{u}^{(j)}_k e^{-2\pi i kx}\in C^{\omega}(\mathbb T)$. We have for each $j\in \mathbb Z_q$, $$\begin{aligned}
    \lambda e^{2\pi i j(j-1)p/q} \hat{u}^{(j)}_{k+1}+\lambda e^{-2\pi i j(j-1)p/q} \hat{u}^{(j)}_{k-1}+e^{-2\pi i ky}\hat{u}^{(j+1)}_k+e^{2\pi i ky}\hat{u}^{(j-1)}_k=E\hat{u}^{(j)}_k,
