Let $\mathcal{H}:=L^2(\mathbb T\times \mathbb Z)$ consisting of functions $u:\mathbb T\times \mathbb Z\to \mathbb C$ such that $$\begin{aligned}
    \sum_{n\in \mathbb Z} \int_{\mathbb T} |u(x,n)|^2\, \mathrm{d}x<\infty,
\end{aligned}$$ and $\mathcal{H}_q:=L^2(\mathbb T\times (\mathbb Z\otimes \mathbb Z_q))$ consisting of functions $\hat{u}:\mathbb T\times (\mathbb Z\otimes \mathbb Z_q)\to \mathbb C$ such that $$\begin{aligned}
    \sum_{m\in \mathbb Z} \sum_{j\in \mathbb Z_q} |\hat{u}(\theta,m,j)|^2\, \mathrm{d}\theta<\infty.
\end{aligned}$$ Define $H^{sk}_{\lambda,y,p/q}$ on $\mathcal{H}$ as follows, $$\begin{aligned}
    (H^{sk}_{\lambda,y,p/q}u)(x,n)=u(x,n+1)+u(x,n-1)+2\lambda\cos(2\pi(x+ny+n(n-1)p/q))u(x,n),
\end{aligned}$$ and $\widehat{H}_{\lambda,y,p/q}$ on $\mathcal{H}_q$ as: $$\begin{aligned}
    (\widehat{H}_{\lambda,y,p/q}\hat{u})(\theta,m,j)
    =&\lambda e^{2\pi i\frac{j(j-1)p}{q}}\hat{u}(\theta,m+1,j)+e^{-2\pi i\frac{j(j-1)p}{q}}\hat{u}(\theta,m-1,j)\\
    &+e^{-2\pi i(\theta+my)}\hat{u}(\theta,m,j+1)+e^{2\pi i(\theta+my)}\hat{u}(\theta,m,j-1).
\end{aligned}$$ Following Chulaevsky-Delyon , we define an unitary operator $U:\mathcal{H}\to \mathcal{H}_q$ as: $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:def_unitary_U}
(Uu)(\theta,m,j)=\sum_{n\equiv j (\mathrm{mod} q)} \int_{\mathbb T} e^{2\pi i(\theta+m y)n}e^{-2\pi i mx} u(x,n)\, \mathrm{d}x.
\end{aligned}$$ A straight-forward computation shows $$\begin{aligned}
    UH^{sk}_{\lambda,y,p/q}=\widehat{H}_{\lambda,y,p/q}U.
\end{aligned}$$ In fact, $$\begin{aligned}
    &(UH^{sk}_{\lambda,y,p/q}u)(\theta,m,j)\\
    =&\sum_{n\equiv j (\mathrm{mod} q)}\int_{\mathbb T} e^{2\pi i(\theta+my)n} e^{-2\pi i mx} (H^{sk}_{\lambda,y,p/q}u)(x,n)\, \mathrm{d}x\\
    =&\sum_{n\equiv j (\mathrm{mod} q)}\int_{\mathbb T} e^{2\pi i(\theta+my)n} e^{-2\pi i mx}(u(x,n+1)+u(x,n-1)\\
    &\qquad +\lambda (e^{2\pi i (x+ny+n(n-1)\frac{p}{q})}+e^{-2\pi i (x+ny+n(n-1)\frac{p}{q})})u(x,n))\, \mathrm{d}x\\
    =&e^{-2\pi i(\theta+my)}(Uu)(\theta,m,j+1)+e^{2\pi i(\theta+my)}(Uu)(\theta,m,j)\\
    &+\lambda e^{2\pi i \frac{j(j-1)p}{q}} (Uu)(\theta,m+1,j)+\lambda e^{-2\pi i\frac{j(j-1)p}{q}}(Uu)(\theta,m-1,j)\\
    =&(\widehat{H}_{\lambda,y,p/q}Uu)(\theta,m,j).
\end{aligned}$$ Hence $\sigma(H^{sk}_{\lambda,y,p/q})=\sigma(\widehat{H}_{\lambda,y,p/q})$, which implies <a href="#eq:claimed_dual" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:claimed_dual">[eq:claimed_dual]</a>, since for irrational $y$, and arbitrary $x,\theta\in \mathbb T$, $$\begin{aligned}
\sigma(H^{sk}_{\lambda,x,y,p/q})=\cup_{x}\sigma(H^{sk}_{\lambda,x,y,p/q})=\sigma(H^{sk}_{\lambda,y,p/q})=\sigma(\widehat{H}_{\lambda,y,p/q})=\cup_{\theta}\sigma(\widehat{H}_{\lambda,\theta,y,p/q})=\sigma(\widehat{H}_{\lambda,\theta,y,p/q}).
\end{aligned}$$

Even under the false <a href="#eq:wrong_1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:wrong_1">[eq:wrong_1]</a>, <a href="#eq:wrong_2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:wrong_2">[eq:wrong_2]</a>, the authors made yet another false claim that $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:wrong_3}
\tilde{f}_{E,n}^-(\theta)=\tilde{f}_{E,n}^-(\theta+\frac{1}{2}).
\end{aligned}$$ However, even under the incorrect equality <a href="#eq:wrong_1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:wrong_1">[eq:wrong_1]</a> and <a href="#eq:wrong_2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:wrong_2">[eq:wrong_2]</a>, one should obtain $\tilde{f}_{E,n}^-(\theta)=\tilde{f}^-_{E,n}(\theta+\omega)$ instead of <a href="#eq:wrong_3" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:wrong_3">[eq:wrong_3]</a>. This is their third critical mistake.

