    \left(\begin{matrix} U_1\\ U_2\end{matrix}\right),
\end{aligned}$$ where $U_1=(...,u_{m+1,B}^2, u_{m+1,B}^1, u_{m,B}^2, u_{m,B}^1,...)^T$ and $U_2=(...,u_{m+1,A}^2, u_{m+1,A}^1, u_{m,A}^2, u_{m,A}^1,...)^T$. This leads to $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:HAB=HH_2}   (H_{\theta}^{AB})^2=\left(\begin{matrix}\widehat{H}_{\theta}\widehat{H}_{\theta}^* &0 \\ 0 &\widehat{H}_{\theta}^* \widehat{H}_{\theta}\end{matrix}\right).
\end{aligned}$$ Therefore, in analogy with <a href="#eq:sig_AA_2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:sig_AA_2">[eq:sig_AA_2]</a>, $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:sig_AB}
    (\sigma(H_{\theta}^{AB}))^2\setminus \{0\}=\sigma((H_{\theta}^{AB})^2)\setminus \{0\}=\sigma(\widehat{H}_{\theta}\widehat{H}_{\theta}^*)\setminus \{0\}.
\end{aligned}$$ The operator $\widehat{H}_{\theta}\widehat{H}_{\theta}^*$ takes the following form: $$\begin{aligned}
(\widehat{H}_{\theta}\widehat{H}_{\theta}^*U)_m=B(\theta+(m+1)\omega)U_{m+1}+V(\theta+m\omega)U_m+B^{(*)}(\theta+m\omega)U_{m-1},
\end{aligned}$$ where $$\begin{aligned}
\label{def:B_AB}
    B(\theta)=\lambda_2\left(\begin{matrix}
        d(\theta-\omega) & 0\\
        \rho &e^{-2\pi i\frac{1}{3}\omega}d(\theta-2\omega)
    \end{matrix}\right),\, B^{(*)}(\theta)=\lambda_2 
    \left(\begin{matrix} c(\theta-\omega) & \rho\\
    0 &e^{2\pi i \frac{1}{3}\omega} c(\theta-2\omega)
    \end{matrix}\right),
\end{aligned}$$ and $$\begin{aligned}
    V(\theta)=
    \left(\begin{matrix}
        c(\theta)d(\theta)+\lambda_2^2 &d(\theta)\\
        c(\theta) &\rho^2+\lambda_2^2+c(\theta-\omega)d(\theta-\omega)
    \end{matrix}\right).
\end{aligned}$$ Let $M_{E,AB}^{HH^*}$ be the cocycle associated to $\widehat{H}_{\theta}\widehat{H}_{\theta}^*U=EU$. Then similarly to Theorems <a href="#thm:HH_loc" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:HH_loc">59</a> and <a href="#thm:AA_loc" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:AA_loc">60</a>, we obtain

<div id="thm:HH_loc_2" class="theorem">

**Theorem 62**. *Let $(\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\lambda_3)$ be such that $\det B(\theta)\neq 0$ on $\mathbb T$, for $B$ as in <a href="#def:B_AB" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="def:B_AB">[def:B_AB]</a>. For a.e. $\omega,\theta\in \mathbb T$, $\widehat{H}_{\theta}\widehat{H}_{\theta}^*$ is Anderson localized in $\{E:\, L_2(\omega, M_{E,AB}^{HH^*})>0\}$.*

</div>

<div id="thm:AB_loc" class="theorem">

**Theorem 63**. *Let $(\lambda_1,\lambda_2,\lambda_3)$ be such that $\det B(\theta)\neq 0$ on $\mathbb T$, for $B$ as in <a href="#def:B_AB" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="def:B_AB">[def:B_AB]</a>. For a.e. $\omega,\theta\in \mathbb T$, $H_{\theta}^{AB}$ is Anderson localized in $\{E:\, E\neq 0, \text{ and }  L_2(\omega,M_{E^2,AB}^{HH^*})>0\}$.*

</div>

Since the proofs are analogous to those of Theorems <a href="#thm:HH_loc" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:HH_loc">59</a> and <a href="#thm:AA_loc" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:AA_loc">60</a>, we don’t repeat them here.

In view of Lemma <a href="#lem:AA_positive" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:AA_positive">61</a>, the purpose of the following lemma is to show that for some regions of the parameters the conditions of Theorems <a href="#thm:HH_loc_2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:HH_loc_2">62</a> and <a href="#thm:AB_loc" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:AB_loc">63</a> are satisfied.

<div id="lem:AB_positive" class="lemma">

*Proof.* Let $\varepsilon_1<0$ be such that $|\tilde{\lambda}_1|=|\tilde{\lambda}_3|e^{2\pi \varepsilon_1}$. Clearly for any $\varepsilon\neq \varepsilon_1$, $d(\theta)\neq 0$ for any $\theta\in \mathbb T$. Hence $\det B(\theta+i\varepsilon)\neq 0$ for any $\theta\in \mathbb T$ and $\varepsilon>\varepsilon_1$. One computes asymptotically in $\varepsilon\to\infty$ that $$\begin{aligned}
B(\theta+i\varepsilon)=e^{2\pi\varepsilon}\lambda_2\lambda_3\left(\left(\begin{matrix}
        e^{-2\pi i(\theta-\omega)} &0\\
        0 &e^{-2\pi i(\theta-2\omega)}
        \end{matrix}\right)+o(1)\right),\, \text{ as } \varepsilon\to \infty,

\end{aligned}$$ $$\begin{aligned}
    B^{(*)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)=\lambda_2\left(\begin{matrix}\lambda_1 & \rho\\ 0 &e^{2\pi i\frac{1}{3}\omega}\lambda_1
    \end{matrix}\right)+o(1),\, \text{ as } \varepsilon\to \infty, 
\end{aligned}$$ $$\begin{aligned}
    B(\theta+i\varepsilon)^{-1}=e^{-2\pi\varepsilon}\frac{e^{2\pi i\theta}}{\lambda_2\lambda_3}\left(\left(\begin{matrix}
        e^{-2\pi i\omega} &0\\
        0 &e^{2\pi i\frac{1}{3}\omega} e^{-4\pi i\omega}
    \end{matrix}\right)+o(1)\right)
\end{aligned}$$ and $$\begin{aligned}
V(\theta+i\varepsilon)=e^{2\pi\varepsilon}e^{-2\pi i\theta}\lambda_3\left(\left(\begin{matrix}
    \lambda_1 & \rho\\
    0 & \lambda_1 e^{2\pi i \omega}
\end{matrix}\right)+o(1)\right),\, \text{ as } \varepsilon\to\infty.

\end{aligned}$$ $$\begin{aligned}
    B^{(*)}(\theta+i\varepsilon)=\lambda_2\left(\begin{matrix}\lambda_1 & \rho\\ 0 &e^{2\pi i\frac{1}{3}\omega}\lambda_1
    \end{matrix}\right)+o(1),\, \text{ as } \varepsilon\to \infty, 
\end{aligned}$$ $$\begin{aligned}
    B(\theta+i\varepsilon)^{-1}=e^{-2\pi\varepsilon}\frac{e^{2\pi i\theta}}{\lambda_2\lambda_3}\left(\left(\begin{matrix}
        e^{-2\pi i\omega} &0\\
        0 &e^{2\pi i\frac{1}{3}\omega} e^{-4\pi i\omega}
    \end{matrix}\right)+o(1)\right)
\end{aligned}$$ and $$\begin{aligned}
V(\theta+i\varepsilon)=e^{2\pi\varepsilon}e^{-2\pi i\theta}\lambda_3\left(\left(\begin{matrix}
    \lambda_1 & \rho\\
    0 & \lambda_1 e^{2\pi i \omega}
\end{matrix}\right)+o(1)\right),\, \text{ as } \varepsilon\to\infty.

\end{aligned}$$ Hence $$\begin{aligned}
    M_{E,AB}^{HH^*}(\theta+i\varepsilon)=\left(\begin{matrix} 
    -\frac{\lambda_1}{\lambda_2}e^{-2\pi i\omega} &-\frac{\rho}{\lambda_2}e^{2\pi i \frac{1}{3}\omega-2\pi i\omega} &\lambda_1\lambda_2 &0\\
    0 &-\frac{\lambda_1}{\lambda_2}e^{2\pi i \frac{1}{3}\omega-2\pi i\omega} &0 &\lambda_1\lambda_2 e^{2\pi i\frac{1}{3}\omega}\\
    0 &0 &0 &0\\
    0 &0 &0 &0
    \end{matrix}\right)+o(1), \text{ as } \varepsilon\to\infty.
\end{aligned}$$ This implies, by the continuity of Lyapunov exponents in the cocycles , similarly to <a href="#eq:lb_L^2_AA_2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:lb_L^2_AA_2">[eq:lb_L^2_AA_2]</a> that $$\begin{aligned}
    L^2_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_{E,AB}^{HH^*})=2\log |\lambda_1/\lambda_2|+o(1), \text{ as } \varepsilon\to\infty.
\end{aligned}$$ By the convexity of $L^2_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_{E,AB}^{HH^*})$ in $\varepsilon$ in the interval $(\varepsilon_1,\infty)$, we have $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:lb_L^2_AB}
    L^2_{\varepsilon=0}(\omega,M_{E,AB}^{HH^*})\geq 2\log |\lambda_1/\lambda_2|\geq \log |\lambda|+O(1).
\end{aligned}$$ In analogy with<a href="#eq:ub_L^1_AA" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:ub_L^1_AA">[eq:ub_L^1_AA]</a>, we now conclude $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:ub_L^1_AB}
    \|M_{E,AB}^{HH^*}(\cdot)\|_{\mathbb T,\infty}\leq \log \left(\frac{(|\lambda_1|+|\lambda_2|+|\lambda_3|+|\rho|)^3}{(|\lambda_3|-|\lambda_1|)^2}\right)+O(1)\leq \log |\lambda|+O(1), 
\end{aligned}$$ uniformly in $|E|\leq 10(\lambda_1^2+\lambda_2^2+\lambda_3^2+\rho^2)$. Combining <a href="#eq:lb_L^2_AB" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:lb_L^2_AB">[eq:lb_L^2_AB]</a> with <a href="#eq:ub_L^1_AB" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:ub_L^1_AB">[eq:ub_L^1_AB]</a> yields the claimed result. ◻

\end{aligned}$$ Hence $$\begin{aligned}
    M_{E,AB}^{HH^*}(\theta+i\varepsilon)=\left(\begin{matrix} 
    -\frac{\lambda_1}{\lambda_2}e^{-2\pi i\omega} &-\frac{\rho}{\lambda_2}e^{2\pi i \frac{1}{3}\omega-2\pi i\omega} &\lambda_1\lambda_2 &0\\
    0 &-\frac{\lambda_1}{\lambda_2}e^{2\pi i \frac{1}{3}\omega-2\pi i\omega} &0 &\lambda_1\lambda_2 e^{2\pi i\frac{1}{3}\omega}\\
    0 &0 &0 &0\\
    0 &0 &0 &0
    \end{matrix}\right)+o(1), \text{ as } \varepsilon\to\infty.
\end{aligned}$$ This implies, by the continuity of Lyapunov exponents in the cocycles , similarly to <a href="#eq:lb_L^2_AA_2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:lb_L^2_AA_2">[eq:lb_L^2_AA_2]</a> that $$\begin{aligned}
    L^2_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_{E,AB}^{HH^*})=2\log |\lambda_1/\lambda_2|+o(1), \text{ as } \varepsilon\to\infty.
\end{aligned}$$ By the convexity of $L^2_{\varepsilon}(\omega,M_{E,AB}^{HH^*})$ in $\varepsilon$ in the interval $(\varepsilon_1,\infty)$, we have $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:lb_L^2_AB}
    L^2_{\varepsilon=0}(\omega,M_{E,AB}^{HH^*})\geq 2\log |\lambda_1/\lambda_2|\geq \log |\lambda|+O(1).
\end{aligned}$$ In analogy with<a href="#eq:ub_L^1_AA" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:ub_L^1_AA">[eq:ub_L^1_AA]</a>, we now conclude $$\begin{aligned}
\label{eq:ub_L^1_AB}
    \|M_{E,AB}^{HH^*}(\cdot)\|_{\mathbb T,\infty}\leq \log \left(\frac{(|\lambda_1|+|\lambda_2|+|\lambda_3|+|\rho|)^3}{(|\lambda_3|-|\lambda_1|)^2}\right)+O(1)\leq \log |\lambda|+O(1), 
\end{aligned}$$ uniformly in $|E|\leq 10(\lambda_1^2+\lambda_2^2+\lambda_3^2+\rho^2)$. Combining <a href="#eq:lb_L^2_AB" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:lb_L^2_AB">[eq:lb_L^2_AB]</a> with <a href="#eq:ub_L^1_AB" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:ub_L^1_AB">[eq:ub_L^1_AB]</a> yields the claimed result. ◻

</div>

*Proof.* By induction in $N$. To deal with the initial scale, we write the operator $\mathcal{H}_x$ defined by <a href="#eq:coupledHarper" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:coupledHarper">[eq:coupledHarper]</a> with Dirichlet boundary conditions on $[0,N]$ in block form $$\mathcal{H}^{(N)}_x = \left [ \begin{matrix}
        A_N& \epsilon \Gamma \\ \epsilon \Gamma^* &  B_N
    \end{matrix}\right]$$ where $A_N, B_N$ are the Harper operators with Dirichlet boundary conditions. By choice of $E$, the Green’s function $(A_N(x)-E)^{-1}$ will be bounded and exponentially decaying for all $x$ and $N$ large enough. Using the Feshbach formula, see Lemma 4.8 in , one reduces the full Green’s function $(\mathcal{H}^{(N)}_x-E)^{-1}$ to the Schur complement $$D_N(x,E):= B_N(x)-E - \epsilon^2 \Gamma (A_N(x)-E)^{-1} \Gamma^*$$ At an initial scale $N_0\gg1$, we control $D_{N_0}(x,E)^{-1}$ perturbatively by taking $\epsilon$ small and $x$ outside a small bad set governed by the LDT for $B_{N}(x)=H^{(N)}_{x,\lambda_2}$: $$\mathrm{mes}(\{ x\in\mathbb{T}\::\: (H^{(N)}_{x,\lambda_2}-E)^{-1} \text{\ \ is not regular\  } \})\le e^{-N^\tau}$$ where $\tau=\tau(\omega,\lambda_2)>0$ and $N$ large. This proves the lemma for $N\in [N_0, N_0^K]$ where $N_0$ is large and some constant $K\ge2\tau^{-1}$. At these initial scales, the complexity bound of $O(N)$ follows from the fact that the connected components of the bad set $\mathcal{B}_{N}(E)$ contain the zeros of $\det(B_{N}(x)-E)$.

For larger scales, we run a multi-scale argument via the resolvent identity and Cartan in the spirit of . Let $N_1\simeq N_0^{C_0}$ where $C_0>1$ is a large constant that will be determined later. For any $x_0\in\mathbb{T}$ we call $n\in [0,N_1]$ *good* if the Green’s function of $\mathcal{H}_{x_0}-E$ restricted to $[0,N_1]\cap [n-N_0,n+N_0]=:J_n$ is regular. The number of bad $n\in [0,N_1]$ does not exceed $O(N_0)$ by the Diophantine condition and the inductive assumption. We write $\Lambda=[0,N_1]=\Lambda_* \cup \Lambda_{**}$ where $$\Lambda_* = \bigcup_{n\text{\ bad}} J_n, \quad \# \Lambda_* \lesssim N_0^2$$ Denote by $G_{\Lambda_{**}}(x,E)$ the Green’s function of $\mathcal{H}_x-E$ restricted to $\Lambda_{**}$ with Dirichlet boundary conditions. By iterating the resolvent identity we conclude that $$\| G_{\Lambda_{**}}(x_0,E)\|\;\mathrm{\lesssim}\;N_0  e^{N_0^\nu},$$ see \*Lemma 2.2. By a standard perturbative Neumann series argument, we further conclude that this bound is locally stable, i.e., $$\| G_{\Lambda_{**}}(z,E)\|\le  e^{N_0}, \qquad \forall\; |z-x_0|<e^{-N_0},\; z\in\mathbb C$$ Locally on $I_0=(x_0-e^{-N_0}, x_0+e^{-N_0})\subset\mathbb{T}$ we write $$\mathcal{H}_x^{\Lambda}-E = \left [ \begin{matrix}
     \mathcal{H}_x^{\Lambda_{*}} -E   &  \Gamma_0 \\   \Gamma_0^* &  \mathcal{H}_x^{\Lambda_{**}} -E
    \end{matrix}\right]$$ where the operators on the diagonal are the restrictions to the respective sets with Dirichlet conditions, while $\Gamma_0$ are the hopping terms. We reduce the Green’s function of the full operator to the Schur complement of this block matrix, viz. $$\mathcal{S}_x := \mathcal{H}_x^{\Lambda_{*}} -E  - \Gamma_0 (\mathcal{H}_x^{\Lambda_{**}} -E)^{-1} \Gamma_0^*$$ Next, we cover $\Lambda$ by intervals $\Lambda_j$ of size $M_0=N_0^K$ to conclude that all $G_{\Lambda_j}(x,E)$ are regular provided $x\in I_0\setminus \mathcal{B}$, where $\mathrm{mes}(\mathcal{B}) \;\mathrm{\lesssim}\;e^{-M_0^\tau} = e^{-N_0^{\tau K}}\ll |I_0|$. By \*Lemma 2.2, Lemma 4.8 we deduce that $\|\mathcal{S}_x^{-1}\|\le e^{M_0}$ for those $x$ as well as by self-adjointness of $\mathcal{S}_x$, $$\log \det(\mathcal{S}_x)\ge -M_0^2 = N_0^{2K}$$ Finally, on the complex disk $\mathbb{D}(x_0, e^{-N_0})$, we have $$\log\det (\mathcal{S}_z)\le |\Lambda_*| N_0 \;\mathrm{\lesssim}\;N_0^3$$ Taking $C_0$ large enough, the Riesz mass of the sub-harmonic function $$u(\zeta )=\log\det (\mathcal{S}_{x_0+\zeta e^{-N_0}})$$ on $\mathbb{D}(0,1)$ is at most $N_0^{2K}=N_1^{{2K}/{C_0}}$. By Cartan’s theorem, $$u(\zeta)> - N_1^{{2K}/{C_0}} N_1^{\tau}> -N_1^{\frac{\nu}{2}}$$ off a set of measure at most $e^{-2N_1^\tau}$ in $\mathbb{D}(0,1)$. Finally, we rescale and sum over the $x$-localization which costs a factor of $e^{N_0}$. By Cramer’s rule, and \*Lemma 4.8, we obtain the first condition of regularity. For the exponential off-diagonal decay, we iterate the resolvent expansion using Green’s functions of the smaller $N_0$ scale, allowing for $N_0^2= N_1^{2/C_0}$ many resonant intervals of that scale within $\Lambda$. See \*Lemma 2.4 for such a procedure in the much more complicated two-dimensional setting. The statement about $O(N)$ connected components follows from the fact that each such component must contain a zero of $\det(\mathcal{H}_x-E)$. ◻
